-- Graded Choice: Axiom of Choice at Credence < 1
--
-- NOTE: This file DEMONSTRATES the proof checker syntax.
-- The actual metatheory is formalized in agda/CredTT/GradedChoice.agda
--
-- LITERATURE: This is more novel than Goedel/consistency work.
-- Related: constructive choice principles (Martin-Loef), realizability.
-- The "credence of AC" idea is CredTT-specific.
--
-- Classical AC: For any family of non-empty sets, there exists a choice function
-- Problem: Non-constructive, leads to paradoxes (Banach-Tarski)
--
-- CredTT alternative: Partial choice at high credence
-- - Finite choice: credence 1 (always works)
-- - Countable choice: credence approaches 1 but may not reach it
-- - Uncountable choice: credence strictly < 1
--
-- Key insight: Paradoxes require credence 1 to be fully realized

-- Finite choice is always possible at credence 1
-- For any finite family {A_1, ..., A_n} of non-empty sets,
-- we can construct a choice function explicitly
postulate finite_choice : Finite_Choice 〔 1 〕

-- Finite induction: if we can choose from n sets, we can choose from n+1
derive choice_step : Choice_n_plus_1 〔 1 〕 from finite_choice by induction

-- For countable families, each finite prefix has a choice function
-- The limit is the full choice function, but the limit may not be achieved
-- Credence = lim_{n->inf} (product of individual credences)
-- If each choice has credence 1-eps_n, total credence = prod(1-eps_n)
-- This can be < 1 even if each factor is close to 1

-- Countable choice at credence approaching 1
provable countable_choice_approx : Countable_Choice 〔 c 〕

-- The credence c satisfies: for any eps > 0, c > 1 - eps for finite prefixes
-- But c may be < 1 in the limit

-- Uncountable choice (full AC) would require credence 1
-- But this may not be achievable

-- Banach-Tarski decomposition:
-- The paradoxical decomposition exists at some credence c < 1
-- This means: the mathematical object is "partially constructed"
-- At credence < 1, it cannot be physically realized

postulate bt_decomposition : Banach_Tarski 〔 c 〕

-- The key constraint: c < 1
-- This is NOT a postulate - it follows from the construction
-- Banach-Tarski requires infinitely many non-constructive choices
-- Each choice contributes a factor slightly < 1
-- The product is strictly < 1

-- Comparison with constructive mathematics:
-- Constructive: AC fails entirely (no choice function)
-- Classical: AC holds fully (credence 1)
-- CredTT: AC holds at credence < 1 (partial choice)
--
-- CredTT is more informative:
-- - We know something exists (credence > 0)
-- - We know it's not fully constructible (credence < 1)
-- - The credence quantifies how "close to constructible" it is

-- Physical interpretation:
-- Credence < 1 means "theoretically possible but not physically realizable"
-- Banach-Tarski at c < 1 correctly predicts: you can't actually do it
-- This resolves the apparent paradox
